Dear Parents/Guardians,

In an effort to prepare for possible extended closure, the West Central School District is looking for your feedback on resources you have available in the home for connecting to learning. If we are called to have school closure for an extended period of time, we intend to provide remote learning access for all of our students. This remote learning access will count as contact hours for your students, meaning that their attendance and participation in the work is required.

Please take the time to fill out the following survey (one survey per household) to help us cater instruction to your students. We would greatly appreciate if you could fill out this survey by 12:00pm tomorrow (3/17). If you are unable to fill out the form electronically please call the schools direct line at 605-528-6229. The line will be open from 5:00 PM – 9:00 PM today, March 16 and 8:00 AM to 12:00 PM March 17.

COVID-19 Superintendent Update - 3:00pm

March 11th, 2020

3:00pm- West Central School District will be closed on Thursday, March 12th and Friday, March 13th. District facilities will be closed until Monday, March 16th. All activities, meetings, and practices are canceled through Sunday, March 15th.

While the South Dakota Department of Health has determined schools need not close, we are committed to completing a thorough cleaning of district facilities and transportation vehicles. School will resume on Monday, March 16th. The end of the 3rd quarter will now be Wednesday, March 18th.

This is the final announcement for today. Further updates will be sent as needed.

Brad Berens
West Central Superintendent

March 11th, 2020

1:00pm- A team of West Central building administrators, supervisors, and our school nurse continue to monitor the COVID-19 situation within our district. A meeting was held with leaders from community childcare centers to share CDC and South Dakota Department of Health recommendations that we are implementing in the West Central Schools.

At 7:30am this morning, West Central School District administration met with county officials to discuss a district action plan in response to the report of a Hartford resident with school-age children testing positive for COVID-19. The adult male identified has not been on district property within the last week.

In consultation with the CDC, South Dakota Department of Health, the Governor’s Office, and local officials, an action plan has been developed to mitigate the potential spread of COVID-19. The district has initiated steps to deep clean all school buildings and sources of transportation. All district buildings are closed and all activities are canceled for today. This includes outside groups who have reserved facility space for Community Education and/or practices.

Please stay tuned to media outlets for further updates and information coming regularly throughout the day.

Brad Berens
West Central Superintendent

post_text:
West Central’s Music Education Program Receives National Recognition

Hartford, SD- April 19, 2018 – West Central has been honored with the Best Communities for Music Education designation from The NAMM Foundation for its outstanding commitment to music education.

The Best Communities for Music Education designation is awarded to districts that demonstrate outstanding achievement in efforts to provide music access and education to all students.

This award recognizes that West Central is leading the way with learning opportunities as outlined in the Every Student Succeeds Act (ESSA). The legislation guides implementation in the states and replaces the No Child Left Behind Act (NCLB) which was often criticized for an overemphasis on testing-while leaving behind subjects such as music. ESSA recommends music and the arts as important elements of a wellrounded education for all children

You are invited to attend tonight’s STUDENT SHOWCASE @ 7PM in the WCHS Auditorium!

This event is FREE, and offers an incredible night of fun and entertainment. Students will perform vocal music pieces, dances, oral interp readings, and instrumental solos. For the second half of the show, the one act play The Princess Who Lost Her Hair will be performed, before the cast takes the play to regional competition this coming Tuesday!

Come out and support our arts programs and our WC students!
There will also be student artwork and projects on display. Silent auction prizes and concessions will be available, with all proceeds benefiting WC Arts.

post_text:
West Central students competed in STEAM-based challenges that spotlight creativity, innovation, teamwork and collaboration skills at the Southeast Area Destination Imagination Regional tournament held at Tri-Valley school on Saturday, March 4th.

Seven West Central teams placed in the top three of their challenge division with six teams moving on and competing at state level in Pierre on Saturday, March 25th.

At the Secondary level, two West Central teams placed first and will be advancing to the State Tournament in Pierre. In the Fine Arts Challenge “Vanished”, the West Central team Vert Couleur Genialite placed first and will be advancing to State Tournament.

In the Scientific Challenge “Top Secret”, the West Central team The 80’s Gang placed first and will be advancing to State Tournament.

Great Job Kids!!!

post_text:
Thank you if you remembered to wear black today.

Let our black clothing honor the 28 lives lost every day due to drunk driving.

Did you know?
Kids who start drinking young are seven times more likely to be in an alcohol-related crash.
One in six teens binge drinks, yet only 1 in 100 parents believe his or her teen binge drinks.
Car crashes are the leading cause of death for teens, and about a quarter of those crashes involve an underage drinking driver.

We can prevent the 4-D’s: Drunk, Drugged, Drowsy and Distracted DRIVING.
Because accidents do happen, please Buckle up. Seat belts SAVE!
It all matters. We all matter!

Youtube video link: https://youtu.be/V2DEM7LMijs

post_text:
THANK YOU if you remembered to wear your neon colors.

Did you know?
Around 10 million people are reported to drive under the influence of illegal drugs every year.
After alcohol, THC, the active ingredient in marijuana, is the substance most commonly found in the blood of impaired drivers, fatally injured drivers, and motor vehicle crash victims.
Studies in several localities have found that approximately 4 to 14 percent of drivers who sustained injury or died in traffic accidents tested positive for THC.

Be more than a statistic. Don’t do drugs or get into a car when someone has been using.

Remember to wear black tomorrow. Together we can Black Out Drunk Driving.

WCHS SADD is on Santa’s nice list! Tuesday night they loaded up on the mini bus for a Random Acts of Kindness Holiday Tour. Christmas goodies and good cheer were randomly delivered across Sioux Falls.
The favorite stop on the tour that warmed everyone's hearts was a random delivery of cupcakes to some very special kids at the Bowden Youth Center in Sioux Falls.
The tour continued through Winter Wonderland in Falls Park where cupcakes were shared with a Sioux Falls Police officer and a couple of tourists visiting Sioux Falls for their first time from Winnepeg Canada!
The last stop on the tour was making a donation toe Make A Wish and enjoying the holiday lights in the Western Mall.

WC Middle School and High School students from Student Council, SADD, Improv and TATU spent the morning learning about 4-D Drunk, Drugged and Distracted Driving. The message of the day seemed to be that our actions have consequences. Sometimes the consequences of 4-D are tragic like death and injury. Some times the consequences of 4-D are stressful like problems with the law. Other times, like today, consequences are good! Good things will come from the good work these teens are doing. We look forward to seeing what ideas they bring back to WC to make our roads safer!
#WhyIBuckle #SeatBeltsSAVE

post_text:
WCHS SADD is asking you to buckle up! Members of SADD teamed up with local law enforcement and emergency first responders to promote a Seat Belts SAVE campaign. A few “warnings" were given warning tickets if they were not buckled up. A majority of the students were buckled up. You are a lifesaver! Thanks for buckling up!
59 Teens were killed in car crashes in SD between 2008-2012.
80% of these teens were not wearing seat belts.
Seat belts could have saved 47 teen lives in South Dakota. Please buckle up!

post_text:
West Central High School SADD celebrated Ally Week. We believe schools should be safe, supportive places for ALL students. The unfortunate truth is that anti-LGBTQ bullying violence and harassment are common place in America’s schools. Allies help put an end to bullying and harassment. Students took this pledge to support Ally Week:
Not use anti-LGBT (lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgender) language or slurs.
Intervene, if I safely can, in situations where students are being harassed.
Support efforts to make this, and every, school safe for all students.

post_text:
6th Annual Indoor Marching Band Concert
Monday, October 20th at 7 p.m. in the new gym

Groups performing will be the High School Marching Trojans, Drumline, Colorguard, and the 8th Grade Band. Each section of the band will be performing a selection too.

The West Central Music Association will be serving “Marching” Tacos, a dessert, and a drink for $5 from 5 p.m .- 6:45 p.m. in the HS commons. Proceeds will go towards scholarships for band students, equipment, and financial help for the East Coast trip this summer. Each section will also create gift baskets that will go to the highest bidder in a silent auction to help them raise money individually for the trip.

The concert usually lasts 55-60 minutes and will be the last time they perform their street and field show. This year has been a historic year for our program and the students are so proud of their show. We hope you can come check it out!

West Central High School
October 8, 2014 at 12:05 PM ·

The WCHS fall play The 39 Steps will be showing in the WCHS Auditorium on Thursday, October 16th @ 7PM and Saturday, October 18th @ 2PM AND 7PM

*Tickets can be purchased at the Hartford Community Library any time next week (Oct. 13-17) during regular business hours, or at the WCHS Auditorium between 6 PM and 7 PM, before each performance.
This is a comedy murder mystery, based on the film by Alfred Hitchcock, but re-written as a “Young Frankenstein-esque stage play”. Our cast of 8 brilliant WCHS students play nearly 40 characters, and the technicians have done an absolutely outstanding job on the productions lighting and sound effects. We are thrilled to present this show at WCHS, and we are sure that the community will love what we’ve created.

See you at the theater!

post_text: West Central has become an affiliate of Health Occupations Students of America also known as HOSA. In 2012, this national organization became established in South Dakota in response to the great need for future health professionals in our state. Recently, numerous high school students at West Central became aware of HOSA and requested that West Central start a HOSA chapter. We have approximately 30 students that are in the process of becoming members of the West Central HOSA chapter.
